NOTES_1JOHN = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: The neuter relative pronoun "ho" (ὅ, "that which") is used rather than the masculine "hos," emphasizing not merely the person of Christ but the fullness of the revelation experienced. "Apsēlaphēsan" (ἐψηλάφησαν, Strong\'s G5584) means to touch, feel, or grope after—a term of physical, tactile contact, stressing incarnational reality against early docetic denials. The perfect tenses "akēkoamen" (we have heard) and "heōrakamen" (we have seen) indicate abiding results of past experience. THEOLOGICAL: "The Word of life" (tou logou tēs zōēs) echoes John 1:1-4, identifying the pre-existent Logos as the source and content of life itself. TYPOLOGY: The "from the beginning" (ap\' archēs) parallels Genesis 1:1 (LXX: en archē) and John 1:1, placing Christ at the origin of all things.',
        2: 'GREEK: "Ephanerōthē" (ἐφανερώθη, Strong\'s G5319) is aorist passive of "phaneroō"—to make visible, to manifest—indicating a decisive divine act of revelation. The life was not discovered but disclosed by God\'s initiative. THEOLOGICAL: "Which was with the Father" (hētis ēn pros ton patera) uses "pros" with the accusative, denoting face-to-face relational presence—the identical construction found in John 1:1 (ho logos ēn pros ton theon). This affirms the eternal pre-existence of the Son in intimate communion with the Father prior to the incarnation.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Koinōnia" (κοινωνία, Strong\'s G2842) denotes shared participation, a deep mutual communion—not mere social association. The fellowship believers enter is nothing less than participation in the communion that exists between the Father and the Son. STRUCTURE: Verse 3 completes the suspended sentence begun in verse 1, finally supplying the main verb "apangellomen" (we declare), creating a rhetorically powerful crescendo from sensory testimony to proclamation to divine fellowship.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: "God is light" (ho theos phōs estin) is an ontological declaration—not merely that God gives light but that he is light in his very essence. "Skotia en autō ouk estin oudemia"—the double negation (ouk...oudemia) is emphatic in Greek, producing an absolute exclusion: no darkness whatsoever exists in him. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Light as a divine attribute pervades the heavenly throne-room imagery of Scripture (Ps 104:2; Dan 7:9-10; Rev 21:23). God\'s nature as pure light establishes the moral foundation for the ethical exhortations that follow in verses 6-10.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Katharizei" (καθαρίζει, Strong\'s G2511) is present active indicative—denoting continuous, ongoing cleansing, not a single past event. TYPOLOGY: The blood that cleanses echoes the Levitical sacrificial system (Lev 16:15-19) and the Passover lamb (Exod 12:13), both fulfilled in Christ. The phrase "from all sin" (apo pasēs hamartias) indicates comprehensive atonement with no category of transgression excluded. THEOLOGICAL: Walking in the light does not mean sinless perfection but living in transparency before God, where the blood of Jesus continually purifies the believer.',
        9: 'GREEK: "Homologōmen" (ὁμολογῶμεν, Strong\'s G3670) means literally "to say the same thing"—to agree with God\'s assessment of our sin. THEOLOGICAL: God\'s forgiveness is grounded in two divine attributes: "pistos" (faithful)—he is bound by his covenant promises—and "dikaios" (righteous)—forgiveness is not a suspension of justice but its satisfaction through the atoning work of Christ (Rom 3:25-26). "Aphē" (ἀφῇ, aorist subjunctive of aphiēmi) means to send away or release, picturing sin as a debt cancelled. "Adikia" (unrighteousness) broadens the scope beyond individual acts to encompass all moral corruption.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Pseustēn poioumen auton"—"we make him a liar"—is among the gravest accusations possible, for it assaults the very character of God who has testified to human sinfulness throughout Scripture (Gen 6:5; Ps 14:3; Rom 3:23). GREEK: "Ho logos autou" (his word) may refer both to the proclaimed gospel message and to Christ himself as the living Word (cf. v. 1; John 1:1), deepening the severity of the denial. The perfect tense "hēmartēkamen" (we have sinned) denotes a settled state—denying not just occasional failings but the abiding reality of human sinfulness.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Paraklētos" (παράκλητος, Strong\'s G3875) means "one called alongside" — an advocate or intercessor. The same term is used by John for the Holy Spirit (John 14:16, 26; 15:26; 16:7). Here it designates Christ\'s ongoing intercessory role before the Father. "Dikaios" (δίκαιος) — "Righteous One" — stands in attributive position emphasizing Christ\'s qualification to advocate on behalf of sinners.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Hilasmos" (ἱλασμός, Strong\'s G2434) denotes propitiation — the turning away of divine wrath through an atoning sacrifice. This is not mere expiation (removal of sin) but satisfaction of God\'s righteous justice. The scope is universal in provision ("the whole world") though applied through faith. This echoes the Day of Atonement typology where the high priest made atonement for all Israel (Lev 16:15-17). TYPOLOGY: Christ fulfills the role of both the sacrifice and the mercy seat (hilastērion, Rom 3:25), the place where God\'s wrath is propitiated.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Teteleiotai" (τετελείωται) is a perfect passive indicative of "teleioō" (Strong\'s G5048), meaning "has been brought to completion" or "has been perfected." The perfect tense indicates a completed action with ongoing results. The love of God reaches its intended goal and completion in the one who keeps His word. THEOLOGICAL: This is not human perfection but the maturation and fulfillment of God\'s covenant love in the obedient believer.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The paradox of a commandment both old and new reflects the inaugurated eschatology of the New Covenant. The love command was given "from the beginning" (Lev 19:18; Deut 6:5), yet is made new in Christ\'s fulfillment and the indwelling Spirit (John 13:34). The darkness "passing away" (paragetai, present tense) indicates the already-not-yet nature of the present age.',
        13: 'STRUCTURE: John addresses three groups — little children (teknia/paidia), fathers (pateres), and young men (neaniskoi) — in a carefully structured double address (vv. 12-14). This may reflect stages of spiritual maturity within the community. "The One from the beginning" (ton ap\' archēs) echoes the prologue of the Gospel of John (John 1:1) and 1 John 1:1, identifying Christ with the eternal Word.',
        16: 'GREEK: "Epithymia" (ἐπιθυμία, Strong\'s G1939) denotes strong desire or craving, not merely temptation. "Alazoneia" (ἀλαζονεία, Strong\'s G212) refers to arrogant boasting or pretentious pride, originally describing a wandering quack or braggart. "Bios" (βίος) here means livelihood or material life, distinct from "zōē" (spiritual/eternal life). TYPOLOGY: This threefold pattern of worldly temptation echoes the temptation of Eve in the Garden — good for food, a delight to the eyes, desirable to make one wise (Gen 3:6) — and Christ\'s threefold temptation in the wilderness (Matt 4:1-11).',
        18: 'HISTORICAL: "Antichristos" (ἀντίχριστος, Strong\'s G500) appears only in 1-2 John in the NT. The prefix "anti-" can mean both "against" and "in place of" Christ. John identifies a singular eschatological antichrist figure yet to come, while noting that many "antichrists" — those embodying the spirit of opposition to Christ — have already arisen. This reflects Second Temple Jewish expectations of an end-time adversary (cf. Dan 7:25; 2 Thess 2:3-4). THEOLOGICAL: The presence of multiple antichrists serves as evidence that the "last hour" (eschatē hōra) has arrived with Christ\'s first advent.',
        20: 'GREEK: "Chrisma" (χρῖσμα, Strong\'s G5545) means "anointing" and is cognate with "Christos" (Anointed One). This refers to the Holy Spirit given to believers, echoing the anointing of priests and kings in the OT (Exod 30:22-33; 1 Sam 16:13). Believers share in the anointing of Christ Himself. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "Holy One" (tou hagiou) from whom the anointing comes likely refers to Christ, who is called the Holy One of God (Mark 1:24; John 6:69), though the Father as source is also possible.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: John defines the essential mark of the antichrist spirit: denial that Jesus is the Christ (the Anointed One, the Messiah). This directly targets early proto-Gnostic and Cerinthian teachings that separated the divine Christ from the human Jesus. To deny the Son is simultaneously to deny the Father — the Father-Son relationship is indivisible in Johannine theology (John 10:30; 14:9-11).',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "chrisma" (anointing) here functions as the internal teacher — the indwelling Holy Spirit who guides believers into all truth (John 16:13). John does not negate the role of human teachers but affirms that the Spirit\'s testimony provides the ultimate criterion for discerning truth from error. The anointing is described as "true" (alēthes) and "not a lie" (ouk estin pseudos), standing in direct contrast to the false teachers of v. 26.',
        29: 'GREEK: "Gegennētai" (γεγέννηται) is perfect passive of "gennaō" (Strong\'s G1080), meaning "has been begotten" or "has been born." The perfect tense indicates an abiding state of divine origin. The passive voice points to God as the agent of this spiritual birth. THEOLOGICAL: Practicing righteousness is not the cause but the evidence of divine begetting — the one born of God bears the family likeness of the Righteous One. This prepares for the major theme of 1 John 3:1-10.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Behold" (ἴδετε, idete) is an aorist imperative of horaō — a command to gaze with astonishment. "What manner of" (ποταπήν, potapēn) expresses quality rather than quantity, conveying wonder at the foreign or extraordinary nature of this love. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "and we are" (καὶ ἐσμέν) is a parenthetical affirmation — not merely a title but an ontological reality. The world\'s failure to recognize believers mirrors its failure to recognize Christ Himself (John 1:10-11).',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "not yet made manifest" (οὔπω ἐφανερώθη) points to an eschatological transformation still awaited. The promise of being "like Him" (ὅμοιοι αὐτῷ) because "we shall see Him just as He is" ties vision of God to glorification — the beatific vision transforms the beholder (2 Cor 3:18). GREEK: φανερωθῇ (phanerōthē) — the same verb used of Christ\'s incarnational appearing — now refers to His return or final revelation.',
        4: 'GREEK: ἀνομία (anomia, Strong\'s G458) means "lawlessness" — not mere transgression but active rebellion against the Torah/divine order. John equates sin (ἁμαρτία) with lawlessness, defining sin not as weakness but as opposition to God\'s established rule. THEOLOGICAL: This identification counters any antinomian tendency that would separate faith from obedience to divine commandment.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "From the beginning" (ἀπ\' ἀρχῆς) echoes Genesis 3 and the primordial rebellion. The Son of God was made manifest (ἐφανερώθη) — the incarnation has a specific cosmic-warfare purpose: to destroy (λύσῃ, lysē — lit. "loose, dissolve, undo") the works of the devil. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This reflects the divine council framework in which the Son enters the domain of rebellious spiritual powers to dismantle their authority (Col 2:15; Heb 2:14). TYPOLOGY: Christ as the seed of the woman (Gen 3:15) crushing the serpent\'s works finds its apostolic interpretation here.',
        9: 'GREEK: "Seed" (σπέρμα, sperma, Strong\'s G4690) refers to divine generative principle — the life-giving reality implanted by God in the believer. "Has been begotten" (γεγεννημένος/γεγέννηται) is perfect tense, indicating a completed action with ongoing results. THEOLOGICAL: The impossibility of sinning for the one begotten of God describes the fundamental incompatibility between the divine nature received and the practice of habitual sin — not sinless perfection but a transformed orientation of life.',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: Cain (Κάϊν) serves as the archetype of the one "of the evil one" (ἐκ τοῦ πονηροῦ) — his murder of Abel prefigures the world\'s hatred of the righteous. The righteous suffer precisely because their works expose the evil of the wicked (Gen 4:1-8). HISTORICAL: In Second Temple Jewish tradition (e.g., Targum Pseudo-Jonathan on Gen 4), Cain was associated with Satanic or demonic paternity, a tradition John appears to affirm.',
        15: 'GREEK: ἀνθρωποκτόνος (anthrōpoktónos, Strong\'s G443) — "murderer," literally "man-slayer." This rare word appears only here and in John 8:44, where Jesus calls the devil a "murderer from the beginning." John thus links hatred of a brother to the character of the devil himself. THEOLOGICAL: The absence of eternal life in the murderer is not merely future judgment but present spiritual reality — hatred is the inward reality of which murder is the outward expression.',
        16: 'GREEK: "Laid down His life" (τὴν ψυχὴν αὐτοῦ ἔθηκεν) echoes Jesus\' own words in John 10:11, 15, 17-18, using the same verb τίθημι. ψυχή here denotes the whole life given in sacrificial death. THEOLOGICAL: The cross is the definitive revelation of what love (ἀγάπη) is — not sentiment but self-sacrifice. The "ought" (ὀφείλομεν) places upon believers a binding obligation to imitate this pattern of costly love.',
        17: 'GREEK: σπλάγχνα (splanchna, Strong\'s G4698) — "bowels," the seat of deep compassion in ancient understanding (comparable to "heart" in modern usage). "Shuts" (κλείσῃ) is an aorist subjunctive indicating a deliberate act of closing off compassion. THEOLOGICAL: The rhetorical question "how does the love of God abide in him?" expects the answer: it does not. Love of God is verified or falsified by material generosity toward the needy brother.',
        23: 'THEOLOGICAL: The singular "commandment" (ἐντολή) encompasses two dimensions: faith and love — believing in the name of Jesus Christ and loving one another. These are not separable obligations but one unified command. GREEK: "Believe in the name" (πιστεύσωμεν τῷ ὀνόματι) uses the dative, indicating trust directed toward and resting upon the person designated by the name. The full title "His Son Jesus Christ" emphasizes divine sonship, historical identity, and messianic office together.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: Mutual abiding — the believer in God and God in the believer — is the culminating theme. The assurance of this indwelling comes "from the Spirit whom He gave to us" (ἐκ τοῦ πνεύματος οὗ ἡμῖν ἔδωκεν). This is the first explicit mention of the Spirit in 1 John, preparing for the extended discussion of discerning spirits in chapter 4. GREEK: πνεύματος (pneumatos, Strong\'s G4151) — Spirit, here the Holy Spirit as the divine agent who mediates and confirms the mutual indwelling of God and believer.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: The verb δοκιμάζετε (dokimazete, Strong\'s G1381) means "to test, examine, prove by trial," used of metals tested by fire. The present imperative indicates an ongoing discipline of discernment. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The plural πνεύματα (pneumata) acknowledges a real spiritual realm of competing spirits—both from God and from the realm of rebellious spiritual beings—requiring believers to exercise discernment (cf. Deut 13:1-5; 1 Cor 12:10).',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The confession test is specifically christological: ὁμολογεῖ Ἰησοῦν Χριστὸν ἐν σαρκὶ ἐληλυθότα—"confesses Jesus Christ having come in the flesh." The perfect participle ἐληλυθότα (elēlythota) indicates a completed action with ongoing results: the incarnation is a permanent reality. HISTORICAL: This targets proto-Gnostic and Docetic teachers who denied the true materiality of Christ\'s body, a serious threat in late first-century Asia Minor.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: The term ἀντίχριστος (antichristos, Strong\'s G500) appears only in 1 John and 2 John in the NT. John identifies the spirit of antichrist not as a future figure alone but as an already-present reality operative through false teachers who deny the incarnation (cf. 1 John 2:18, 22; 2 John 7).',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The perfect tense νενικήκατε (nenikēkate, "you have overcome") indicates a decisive and abiding victory. The comparative μείζων (meizōn, "greater") establishes a contrast between the Holy Spirit indwelling believers and the spiritual power animating the world system (cf. John 12:31; 16:11). DIVINE_COUNCIL: This verse presupposes a cosmic conflict between God and hostile spiritual powers, with believers participating in Christ\'s victory over the rulers of this age.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The declaration ὁ θεὸς ἀγάπη ἐστίν ("God is love") is one of the most profound ontological statements in Scripture. Note that John does not say "love is God" but "God is love"—love is an essential attribute of God\'s nature, not a definition that reduces God to an abstract concept. The aorist ἔγνω (egnō) suggests the one not loving never truly came to know God at all.',
        9: 'GREEK: The term μονογενῆ (monogenē, Strong\'s G3439) means "only-begotten" or "one-of-a-kind, unique." It denotes the singular, unrepeatable relationship of the Son to the Father. TYPOLOGY: The sending of the only-begotten Son echoes Abraham\'s offering of Isaac (Gen 22:2, 12, 16 LXX where μονογενής is used), establishing a typological link between the Aqedah and God\'s sacrificial gift (cf. John 3:16).',
        10: 'GREEK: The word ἱλασμόν (hilasmon, Strong\'s G2434) means "propitiation"—an offering that turns away divine wrath by satisfying the demands of justice. It appears in the NT only here and in 1 John 2:2. THEOLOGICAL: John emphasizes the initiative of divine love: the propitiation originates not in human effort toward God but in God\'s own self-giving act of sending His Son. Love and wrath are not contradictory; the cross satisfies both (cf. Rom 3:25).',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: θεὸν οὐδεὶς πώποτε τεθέαται ("No one has ever beheld God") echoes John 1:18. The perfect tense τεθέαται emphasizes that no human has ever gazed upon God in His unveiled essence. Yet God\'s invisible presence becomes tangibly manifest through mutual love among believers—His love is τετελειωμένη (teteleiōmenē, "perfected, brought to its intended completion") in the community.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: The Father\'s sending (ἀπέσταλκεν, apostalken, perfect tense—sent with abiding result) of the Son as σωτῆρα τοῦ κόσμου ("Savior of the world") declares the universal scope of Christ\'s saving mission. The title σωτήρ was used in the imperial cult for Caesar; John\'s application to Christ is a direct counter-claim to Roman imperial theology (cf. John 4:42).',
        17: 'GREEK: παρρησίαν (parrēsian, Strong\'s G3954) denotes "boldness, confidence, freedom of speech"—originally a political term for the citizen\'s right to speak freely in the assembly. Here it describes the believer\'s confidence before the divine Judge. THEOLOGICAL: The basis for this boldness is ontological conformity: καθὼς ἐκεῖνός ἐστιν καὶ ἡμεῖς ἐσμεν—"just as that One is, so also are we." Present-tense identification with Christ in this world becomes the ground of fearlessness on the day of κρίσεως (kriseōs, judgment).',
        18: 'GREEK: The verb βάλλει (ballei, "casts out") is vivid and forceful—the same verb used for casting out demons (Mark 1:34). Perfect love does not merely reduce fear; it violently expels it. The term κόλασιν (kolasin, Strong\'s G2851) means "punishment" or "torment," indicating that fear itself carries a punitive, tormenting quality incompatible with the perfection of love.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: The priority of divine love is the theological foundation of the entire chapter. The pronoun αὐτός (autos, "He") is emphatic, and πρῶτος (prōtos, "first") establishes absolute temporal and causal priority: God\'s love is not a response to ours but its origin and cause (cf. Rom 5:8; Eph 2:4-5).',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Begotten" (γεγέννηται, gegennētai, perfect passive of gennaō, Strong\'s G1080) indicates a completed divine act with ongoing results. The perfect tense emphasizes the abiding state of one who has been born of God. THEOLOGICAL: John ties together faith in Jesus as the Christ (Messiah) with divine begetting — belief is both evidence and fruit of regeneration. The familial logic is striking: to love the Father who begets is inseparable from loving those begotten by Him.',
        4: 'GREEK: "Overcomes" (νικᾷ, nika, Strong\'s G3528) is present tense, indicating ongoing victory, while "has overcome" (νικήσασα, nikēsasa) is aorist participle — a decisive, accomplished victory. THEOLOGICAL: The victory over the world-system (kosmos) is attributed not to human effort but to the new-birth origin ("begotten of God") and its instrument, faith. This echoes Jesus\' declaration in John 16:33: "I have overcome the world."',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Water and blood" most likely refers to the baptism and crucifixion of Jesus Christ, the bookends of His public ministry. John counters early docetic or Cerinthian heresy that denied Christ came in true flesh or that the divine Christ departed before the cross. GREEK: The emphatic repetition — "not by the water only, but by the water and by the blood" — uses the Greek article (τῷ) to make each element specific and definite. The Spirit (τὸ πνεῦμα, to pneuma) serves as the ongoing divine witness to these historical realities.',
        7: 'HISTORICAL: The longer reading known as the Comma Johanneum (adding "in heaven: the Father, the Word, and the Holy Spirit, and these three are one") found in some Latin manuscripts is absent from all early Greek manuscripts and is widely regarded as a later interpolation. The critical Greek text preserves only the shorter reading presented here.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The threefold witness of Spirit, water, and blood corresponds to the requirements of Deuteronomy 19:15 that testimony be established by two or three witnesses. The three converge "unto the one" (εἰς τὸ ἕν) — they agree in a single, unified testimony concerning the identity and saving work of Jesus Christ.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse presents the most distilled summary of Johannine soteriology: eternal life is exclusively mediated through the Son. The starkly parallel construction — having the Son equals having life; not having the Son equals not having life — allows no middle ground. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the pattern of life being found only "in" God\'s appointed means, as the tree of life was in Eden (Gen 2:9) and as Israel\'s life was in covenant obedience (Deut 30:19-20).',
        18: 'GREEK: There is a crucial distinction between "the one having been begotten" (ὁ γεγεννημένος, ho gegennēmenos, referring to the believer) and "the One begotten" (ὁ γεννηθείς, ho gennētheis, aorist passive, referring to Christ). THEOLOGICAL: Christ, as the uniquely begotten Son, is the one who guards (τηρεῖ, tērei) the believer so that the evil one (ὁ πονηρός, ho ponēros — Satan) cannot "touch" (háptō, Strong\'s G680, meaning to fasten oneself to, to cling to with harmful intent) him. This is divine preservation, not sinless perfection.',
        19: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The stark contrast — "we are of God" versus "the whole world lies in the evil one" — reflects a cosmic dualism of allegiance, not ontological dualism. The evil one (ὁ πονηρός) is the usurping ruler of the present world-system (cf. John 12:31, 2 Cor 4:4, Eph 2:2), a rebellious member of the spiritual realm whose dominion Christ has come to overthrow. GREEK: "Lies" (κεῖται, keitai) suggests a passive, helpless state — the world is laid down in the power of the evil one.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: "This One is the true God and eternal life" (οὗτός ἐστιν ὁ ἀληθινὸς θεὸς καὶ ζωὴ αἰώνιος) is one of the strongest Christological affirmations in the New Testament. The proximate referent of "this one" (houtos) is Jesus Christ, identifying Him directly as "the true God" (ho alēthinos theos). GREEK: "Understanding" (διάνοιαν, dianoian, Strong\'s G1271) refers to the faculty of intellectual and spiritual perception — the Son has granted a renewed mind capable of knowing the True One. TYPOLOGY: The "True One" (τὸν ἀληθινόν) echoes the covenant name theology of the Old Testament where YHWH alone is the true and living God over against all idols (cf. Jer 10:10), setting up the final exhortation in v.21.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: The abrupt closing — "guard yourselves from idols" (εἰδώλων, eidōlōn, Strong\'s G1497) — is not a non sequitur but the natural conclusion of the entire epistle. Any object of ultimate allegiance that is not the true God revealed in Jesus Christ is an idol. DIVINE_COUNCIL: In Second Temple Jewish thought, idols were understood as connected to rebellious spiritual beings (cf. Deut 32:17; Ps 106:37; 1 Cor 10:20). John\'s warning thus carries both theological and spiritual-warfare dimensions.',
    },
}